question: If a star has an apparent magnitude of 0.9592846330762328 in the V-band from Earth, and is located at a distance of 4978.4051957401125 parsecs, what would be its absolute magnitude?
code:
import numpy as np
from astropy import units as u

magnitude = 0.9592846330762328
distance = 4978.4051957401125
absolute_magnitude = magnitude - 5 * (np.log10(distance) - 1)
print(absolute_magnitude)

question: When it's 2023-09-07T23:59:59 UTC, what would be the solar zenith angle at latitude 35.11318423689838° and longitude 101.6848535920252°?
code:
from astropy.coordinates import get_sun, EarthLocation, AltAz
from astropy.time import Time
from astropy import units as u

location = EarthLocation(lat=35.11318423689838*u.deg, lon=101.6848535920252*u.deg)
time = Time('2023-09-07T23:59:59')
altaz = get_sun(time).transform_to(AltAz(obstime=time, location=location))
zenith_angle = 90 * u.deg - altaz.alt
print(zenith_angle)

from astropy.coordinates import get_sun, EarthLocation, AltAz
from astropy.time import Time
from astropy import units as u

location = EarthLocation(lat=26.4238487576808*u.deg, lon=-76.55283251069334*u.deg)
time = Time('2023-09-07T12:00:00')
altaz = get_sun(time).transform_to(AltAz(obstime=time, location=location))
zenith_angle = 90 * u.deg - altaz.alt
print(zenith_angle)

starB = SkyCoord(ra=161.07213985624753*u.degree, dec=-24.55971741116538*u.degree, frame='icrs')
angular_separation = starA.separation(starB)

from astropy.coordinates import SkyCoord, EarthLocation, AltAz
from astropy.time import Time
from astropy import units as u

body = SkyCoord(ra=119.41734486401774*u.degree, dec=-41.2834286387362*u.degree, frame='icrs')
location = EarthLocation(lat=6.165492843253205*u.deg, lon=0.08991793264078751*u.deg)
time = Time('2023-09-07T00:00:00')
altaz = body.transform_to(AltAz(obstime=time, location=location))
altitude = altaz.alt
print(altitude)
